It's time to play! The players are on the field. The Barmy Army is done with its anthem. Joe Root and Jonny Bairstow are the overnight batsmen for England. It's going to be Mohammed Shami to begin proceedings. Root to face. Here we go...
Did you know? On this day, in 1990, a 17-year old Sachin Tendulkar stroked his maiden international century (119*) to save a Test match for India against England in Manchester.

Pitch report - Nick Knight says that there is still some green tinge on the surface and that might encourage the seamers. Informs that there are a few red marks and the ball stayed a bit low last evening and the edges didn't carry. Opines that it's still a very good pitch for batting and there is no problem as such. Advices India to bring the keeper up a few steps and accordingly place the fielders in the slip cordon.

A quick word with Ravindra Jadeja! 'Sir' says that they have put up a good total on the board and they need early wickets today to get in the driver's seat. Feels that if they restrict England under 250 and they will be on top in the game. Tells that you have to play according to your plans, utilize your brains and execute your skills. Praises the opening stand of Rohit and Rahul.
Just in - Former Indian cricketer, Farokh Engineer will be ringing the five-minute bell at Lord's this morning.

The star with the ball on Day 2 and the legend of the English bowling attack, James Anderson has a word. Jimmy says that India probably still have the edge but if England can get a couple of big partnerships, they will be right back in the game. Feels that they are not out of the game but have a lot of hard work to do. As per him, England will have to bat the day to get near India. Regarding England's turnaround with the ball after Day 1, Anderson replies that they assessed their performance and thought they didn't do a lot wrong. Tells that they planned to put their best ball in the right area to get rewards. Credits Rahul and Rohit for the way they played. Mentions that he never feels pressurized due to the responsibility and adds that Ollie Robinson may be new to Test cricket but he has played plenty of FC cricket. Further adds that Mark Wood and Sam Curran also have good exposure to international cricket so he doesn't have to do a lot of leading. States that his job mainly is to set the right tone with the ball. On his fitness, Jimmy replies that it was just a precautionary scan before this Test match but it was nothing more than stiffness.

Weather - We are so delighted to type that it's BRIGHT AND SUNNY! Looks like a perfect day for batting. Michael Atherton was on air a little while back and said that Day 3 is considered to be the best batting day at Lord's but at the same time, the Englishman reminded that due to the slope, the bowlers always get some assistance. It's going to be a great battle between bat and ball.

Joe Root, the wall of England. You can also say it's Root who is standing in the way of India once again with yet another fabulous knock. His stay at the crease is going to be inversely proportional to India's chances of gaining a big lead. The visitors would have to smartly strategize against him and if removing him is difficult, at least, India should not offer him freebies. The rest of the English batting can be termed 'as reliable as the English weather' so there would be an opening always for the tourists at the opposite end. The morning session of Day 3 holds great importance and that would decide the pathway of this Test match.

Two beautiful days of Test cricket at the Mecca and it's set up nicely. Punches have been exchanged with India landing theirs on the first day and England giving the uppercut on the following day. It could have been a perfect Day 2 for the Three Lions had they not lost Rory Burns late in the evening. Still, the hosts need to be credited for the way they bounced back after a not-so-convincing first day. This Test match hangs in the balance but India would like to believe that it's tilted in their favour. We won't argue much as having a 200-plus lead heading into the third day can be considered more than handy and England have a lot of catching up to do. On that note, allow us to welcome you all for the coverage and stay tuned for more...

That's a wrap to the second day's play. India had the opportunity to bat England out of the game but they didn't take it and as a result, this Test match is still wide open, however, the touring team has its noses in front. England trail by 246 runs but they have only one batsman in Joe Root on whom they can rely as the rest of the batters are yet to show promise. Day 3 is called the moving day and let's see which way the Lord's Test moves. The action on Saturday will begin at 10 am GMT (11 am local) but you can join us early for the build-up. Cheers!

England's reply with the bat started on the right note as their openers saw off the initial period safely. But as was the trend on Friday, a couple of wickets fell in quick succession and that spoiled all the hard work done by Burns and Sibley. The Indian bowlers were decent but only in patches. Mohammed Siraj claimed a couple of wickets and Mohammed Shami picked one late in the day. For some unknown reasons, Shami was underutilized by Virat Kohli. Returning from an injury break, Ishant Sharma spent his time bowling within himself and looked rusty whereas Jasprit Bumrah was not at his best.

Earlier in the day, India failed to drive home the advantage. They were in a great position but slipped miserably from there. The visiting team managed just 88 runs and lost the remaining 7 wickets without giving much resistance. Only Rishabh Pant and Ravindra Jadeja offered a fight and their knocks pushed India's total past the 350-run mark. Once again it was James Anderson doing the damage with five wickets and England finally did what they had planned for Day 1 after deciding to bowl first.

Another well-fought session comes to a close! India started it with a bang as Mohammed Siraj picked two wickets in the very first over after Tea. With Dominic Sibley and Haseeb Hameed departing off consecutive deliveries, there was big pressure on England but in walked Joe Root and he once again looked class apart. His 85-run stand with Rory Burns kept India at bay for almost the entire session before Mohammed Shami got one to curl back in and trapped Burns in front of the wickets. 96 runs for 3 wickets - That was the story of the final session and this Test match has moved at a steady rate.
Fuller in length and on off, Bairstow defends it watchfully. That will be STUMPS ON DAY 2!
Smart thinking from the bowler. Goes for an inswinging yorker, trying to catch the batsman off-guard, Jonny Bairstow does well to dig it out safely.
Indipper this time, on a length around off, Jonny defends it from the inner half to the leg side.
Beaten! Great ball again. On a length and outside off, holding its line, Jonny hangs his bat out in defense but the ball whistles past the outside edge.
Close to off, on a good length, shaping in, Bairstow strides forward and across before defending it with a dead bat.
Root moves to 48! Full in length and on middle, nipping in, Root tries to flick but it takes the inner half and rolls to fine leg. They cross.
Superb leave. Full in length and outside off, shaping in, Bairstow takes his front leg away from the line of stumps and then shoulders arms.
Full and swinging in around off, Bairstow gets on the front foot and defends it back.
Good length delivery outside off, shaping in, JB offers no shot.
Uses the angle of the bowler and works it in the gap on the leg side for one.
Fuller in length and on middle, Jonny clips it through square leg for a single.
On a length and outside off, Root plays late and places it wide of point for a run.
The line is wide outside off, Jonny shoulders arms.

Huge shout for a caught behind, not given! Excellent delivery, full and around off, straightening off the seam, Bairstow gets across the stumps, is squared up slightly in defense as it beats the bat. There is some sound as the ball goes to Pant and Siraj starts to celebrate. The umpire remains unmoved. The replays show that the noise was of the ball clipping the flap of the back pad. Rightly Kohli didn't waste any more review.
Gets forward to a full all and blocks it to the off side.
The batsman has just watchfully blocked this out.
Fullish and outside off, Bairstow drives it off his front foot to covers.
On a length and outside off, Root eases it down to third man for a run.
Fuller length ball outside off, Root taps it down to covers and takes a single.

FIVE RUNS! A length ball around off, Bairstow brings down a straight bat to defend but it takes the outer half and rolls to the left side of point. Jadeja attacks the ball, has a shy at the bowler's end as Bairstow goes for a run. It's a wayward throw and the mid on fielder probably was not expecting it to his left side, probably was anticipating a shy at the striker's end and was moving to his right. Boundary results.
An overpitched delivery outside off, Bairstow allows it through.
Full and on off, the batsman has just blocked that from his crease.
Jonny Bairstow is the new batsman. Not a good time to walk in.

OUT! Rory Burns is caught plumb in front! Shami speeds in from 'round the wicket and lands it on a length close to off. The ball lands and jags back in to beat the attempted flick shot from Burns. He is pinged on the pads, the appeal is made and the finger has gone up. Rory takes the DRS but to no use. Only an inside edge could have saved him. But the bat is absent. The Ball Tracker shows THREE REDS. Burns departs late in the day, one short of his fifty. England trail by 256 runs.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Mohammed Shami

Commentary.Commentary: Mohammed Shami is back on, 0/13 in 6 overs so far.
Begins his spell with a good length delivery outside off, Burns allows it through to the keeper.
Shortish and on middle, Burns tucks it to deep square leg for a single.

100 up for England! Floated ball, landing full around off, Root pushes it gently to cover-point and steals a single. Also, Root completes 2000 Test runs against India.
Fires a full ball on off, Burns flicks it to square leg for a single.

Shortish again, around off, dabbed down in the gap at covers for one.

Fuller and on middle, flicked to deep mid-wicket for a couple of runs.

Fuller in length and outside off, Root mistimes his drive back in the direction of the bowler.
Shortish length ball on off, Root defends it from the back foot to the off side.

Drinks break. England have recovered decently after a dramatic first over after Tea where they lost two wickets. Joe Root and Rory Burns have settled down to form a partnership. We're back! Get ready for a long last session as 38 overs are pending. The men concerned are out in the middle. Burns and Sibley have done well so far but can they capitalize and make this start count? Mohammed Siraj will continue from this end after the break. All in readiness, here we go...
... DAY 2, THIRD SESSION ...

A quiet session in terms of runs! England didn't take long to pick the remaining three Indian wickets after Lunch and bowled them out for 364. James Anderson picking yet another 5-wicket haul was the highlight of the afternoon period of play. In response, the English openers have batted for 14 overs without much discomfort. Both, Dominic Sibley and Rory Burns have faced 42 balls each and have scored 11 runs apiece. The Indian bowlers tried hard but didn't succeed in getting the first breakthrough. There were a few edges but they didn't carry to the slip cordon. The hosts would be pleased with the way Day 2 has gone so far and would be aiming to finish strongly in the evening. Do join us at 3 pm GMT (4 pm local) for more attritional cricket.
Beaten! Zippy delivery, a touch short and outside off, Burns pokes inside the line and misses. That will be TEA ON DAY 2!
Fuller in length and on off, Burns tries to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads. The ball rolls to the off side, Rory looks for a run but Sibley sends him back.
Sliding down the leg side, tickled to fine leg for a run.

Huge shout for a caught behind! Not given. Fractionally short, outside off and curling away, Sibley feels for it and gets beaten. It goes very closely past the edge as Pant collects. The Indians appeal but the umpire stays still. Kohli has a word with his players, Pant is unsure, someone said he heard a noise, Virat thinks and thinks and then decides not to take the DRS.
Shami bowls it on a fuller length around middle, Dominic Sibley flicks it behind square leg for a couple of runs.
Serves a good length delivery, close to off and gets it to shape away, Sibley reads the plan and ignores the delivery.
Shami runs in but loses the ball before he can deliver. Dead ball signalled.
Shortish and on top of off, Burns defends it off his back foot. Just enough time left for one more over.
Fractionally short again, around middle and leg, Burns turns it behind square leg but finds the fielder.
Back of a length, around middle and off, Burns goes on the back foot and taps it down defensively to the off side.
Angling away from the batsman, Burns has a tame push inside the line and misses.

Aerial but safe! What's Burns trying with Tea around the corner? Fetches a short ball from wide outside off, doesn't middle his shot properly and pops it out away from short mid-wicket. Two runs taken.

Play and a miss! Not needed, Rory. Siraj begins with a shortish ball around off, Burns tries to pull but fails to connect. Pant does well to dive across to his right as he stops the ball with one hand.
Double bowling change. Mohammed Siraj is also into the attack.
Fractionally short and outside off, Sibley hangs back and punches it through covers. Doesn't try to hit it hard, just pierces the gap and the slope takes the ball away. Two runs taken.
Plays late. A length ball on off, shaping away a bit, Sibley sticks on the back foot and defends it late with an angled bat.
This time Shami has angled a length ball around off, Sibley defends it from the crease.
Outswinger from Shami but the line is too wide outside off, allowing Sibley to have an easy leave.
Fuller again, around off, Dominic defends it to the off side, finds covers.
Straightaway beats the edge with a beauty! Fuller in length and around off, landing on an upright seam and moving away slightly to beat Sibley's defensive bat.
Mohammed Shami is introduced into the attack with 10 minutes left in this session.
Fullish and wide outside off, an outswinger, Burns has the option of driving but he doesn't want to play away from his body.

Back of a length, outside off, Sibley punches it through the gap at backward point. They take a run, want the second but there is hesitation as it's Jadeja attacking the ball. Sibley has taken off, there is a little fumble from Jadeja but Burns is loud and clear in sending his partner back.
A touch short and around off, Sibley gets across a bit and plays it down to short mid-wicket.
Ishant bends his back and delivers it around off, Sibley leans back and sways away.
Looks like the studs have come off from Mohammed Siraj's shoes. He is down on the ground, fixing it. Maybe, he will get an over or two before Tea.
Close to off, on a length and angling in, Sibley defends it to covers.
Good length delivery but too wide outside off, Sibley has an easy leave.
This time the line is too straight and the length allows Burns to work it away towards mid-wicket. 10 overs are safely negotiated by the English openers.
Bumrah continues to probe around leg and it moves towards off, Burns tries to defend but gets an inside edge onto the back thigh pad.
Fuller in length and outside off, angling away, Burns plants his front foot forward to cover his stumps and then makes a leave.
Fractionally short and around leg, Burns tucks it away but finds the fielder at square leg.
Bumrah pitches it up around leg, getting it to move away, Burns is opened up a bit in his stance as he defends it from the outer half of his bat to covers.
Back of a length, around leg and angling away, Rory stays on the back foot and defends it down to the off side.
Gets closer to the off stump line, fuller in length and shaping in, Sibley is forward as he defends it right under his nose.
Bowls it full and wide outside off, Dominic has nothing to do with it.

Movement and bounce. Ishant gets it to tail back in from a length around off, Sibley fails to keep it out and is struck on the pads. We heard the Indians appealing but Ishant himself is not joining them.
Ishant Sharma repeats the last delivery, Dominic Sibley also repeats his last act. Offers no shot.
Ishant tries to tempt the batsman with a driving length delivery outside off, Sibley is watchful and doesn't want to do anything flashy. Leaves.
A length delivery outside off, Dominic Sibley makes an easy leave.
Good length delivery in the channel outside off, left alone by Burns.
The line is too straight and Sibley works it behind square leg for a single.
Edged again, safe again. Sibley tries his best to defend a delivery around off, does so with soft hands and the outside edge falls short once more.
Edged but safe! Sibley pushes inside the line from the back foot and edges it behind. It doesn't carry to the slip cordon.
A length ball, on off. Sibley defends it back to the bowler with a straight bat.
A full length ball, around leg. Sibley looks to flick it to the on side, but the ball takes the outer half and goes back towards the bowler.
A full length ball, around off. Burns defends it out to the left of extra cover. Cheteshwar Pujara moves to his left to make the stop.

A good length ball, angling in around middle and leg and there is some extra bounce. Burns tries to defend but is squared up. It possibly takes the inside edge and hits him on the thigh pad. The ball falls near the popping crease and stays stationary. Rory though thought it's rolling back and gets ready to kick it away. Meanwhile, he hears a shout of Rory from his partner who wants to steal a run but Burns is too occupied and turns down the proposal.
A full length ball, on off. Burns comes forward and blocks it out solidly.
A length ball, around off. Burns stays back and defends it to the off side.
FOUR! A loosener and Burns makes the most of it. A length ball, sliding down the leg side. Burns flicks it past Rishabh Pant and the ball ends up going to the boundary at fine leg.
Sharma comes 'round the wicket for the left-hander. A length ball, around off, swinging in. Burns stays back and defends it out to the off side.
Good length ball, outside off. Sibley shoulders his arms this time. 36 balls done and the English openers have survived the initial phase without much discomfort.
A length ball, on off. Sibley defends it out from the outer half of his bat.
BEATEN AGAIN! A full length ball, just outside the off stump. Sibley is tempted by it and goes for the booming cover drive but misses.
BEATEN! On a length, outside off. The ball nips away off the pitch. Sibley looks to have a poke at it but misses. The ball zips past the outside edge.
A length ball, on the pads. Burns flicks it to deep square leg. The batters take three before Mohammed Siraj cuts it off near the ropes.
Bumrah angles in on middle from around off. Burns stays back and keeps it out.
A maiden for Ishant Sharma now. A full length ball, on off. Sibley defends it out watchfully.
A full length ball, around off. Making Sibley play at it. He defends it towards mid on off the inner half of the blade.
On a length, outside off, the ball nips in a bit. Sibley shoulders his arms.
Good length ball, outside off. Sibley has no interest in playing any ball that is pitched away from him.
Sharma serves it on a length, outside off. The ball holds its line after pitching. Sibley has no stroke to offer.
Good length ball, outside off, jagging in. Sibley lets it go to the keeper.

Once again the umpire walks down the pitch. He watches the followthrough and has a quiet word with Ishant, asking him to stay away from the danger area. So, both the Indian pacers are flirting with danger at the moment. No official warning yet.
A length ball, outside off, an outswinger this time. Left alone by Rory Burns. Another maiden for Bumrah.
Good judgement by Rory Burns. Jasprit Bumrah serves a length ball, outside off. The ball nips in a bit. Rory Burns trusts the bounce and shoulders his arms.
A full length ball, on the pads. Burns clips it to mid-wicket but straight to the fielder.
Good length ball, outside off. Burns is happy to let that one go to the keeper.
The umpire is having a closer look at the danger area after Jasprit Bumrah finished his last ball. No warning, no quiet word. But his gesture would have sent the signal.
On a length, around off. Burns stays inside the crease and defends it out,
Now Bumrah comes 'round the wicket. A length ball, outside off. The ball nips away off the pitch. Burns lets it go to the keeper.

FOUR! Nice shot! A full length ball, around off, swinging in a bit. Dominic Sibley drives it down the ground by showing the full face of his willow. The ball ends up at the long on fence. This is just amazing from the batsman. Well played.
An inswinger yet again. Full and on off. Sibley defends it out watchfully but off the inner half of his blade.
A short leg in place. Virat Kohli tosses up the helmet to Cheteshwar Pujara who is the fielder under the lid. Standing a bit deep than the usual position.
A length ball, outside off. Sibley lets it go to the keeper.
A bit of an inswing now. Sharma serves it on a length, around off. The ball comes in. Sibley looks to defend it out but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Sharma comes over the wicket now for the right-hander. A good length ball, outside off. Sibley shoulders his arms without any hesitation.
Sharma comes 'round the wicket. He serves it on a length, around middle. Burns flicks it towards fine leg. They take one.

BEATEN! Jasprit Bumrah with a beauty to end the over! He serves it in the corridor of uncertainty. On a length, just outside off. Sibley looks to defend it out but misses. The ball beats the outside edge.
LEG BYE! A full length ball, on the pads. Burns looks to flick it away but misses. The ball clips the pads and rolls towards fine leg. The batters collect a leg bye.
Good length ball, outside off. Burns has no stroke to offer this time.
Quicker. On a length, outside off. The ball is moving away from the batsman. Burns lets it go to the keeper.
A good length ball, outside off. Coming across the left-hander. Burns watches the ball carefully and shoulders his arms.
Bumrah starts his spell with a length ball, down the leg side. Burns leaves it alone.
Jasprit Bumrah to share the new ball from the opposite end.
A length ball, around middle and off. Burns taps it down to mid-wicket and takes off for a single. Rory Burns and England are off the mark.
A length ball, on off. Burns defends it out watchfully.

Did it carry? Oh no, it didn't. Sharma serves a length ball, around off. There is some away movement on the ball. Burns looks to defend it out with an angled bat. The ball though takes the outside edge, it falls just short of Rohit Sharma at second slip. Kohli was ready to celebrate but then he saw Rohit Sharma continued to stay down on the ground, suggesting it didn't carry.
A length ball, on off. Burns defends it out solidly.
Sharma serves a length ball, around middle and off. Burns defends it onto the pitch. Looked like he was unaware of the position of the ball after he played it.
Sharma starts with a length ball, around off. Burns moves across and defends it out solidly.

The players have returned on the field. India are in a huddle. 60 overs should feel like hell for England, that's the message from Kohli to his boys. It's quite gloomy out there and the artificial lights are switched on. Kohli also have a word with the umpires, maybe this is regarding the light. A big challenge awaits Dominic Sibley and Rory Burns.​ Jasprit Bumrah to steam in...

Will England go after the target? They have a very shaky top order and once again the onus will be on Joe Root. The Indian bowlers will be fired up after what happened in the morning session and would be keen to give it back. It's shaping up to be a tasty finish. Stay tuned.

Let's quickly summarize this innings. India started on the wrong note after trailing by 27 runs and were struggling with three top order batsmen back in the hut. The century stand between Cheteshwar Pujara and Ajinkya Rahane bailed them out and put them in a decent position. However, England bounced back last evening to remove both the set batsmen along with Ravindra Jadeja. The visitors were struggling to swell their lead even to 200 and all their hopes were on Rishabh Pant this morning. But as we saw, it was the unexpected 89-run stand between Bumrah and Shami that handed them the momentum and the upper hand. England's bowling blew hot and cold and as a result, they find themselves in a precarious situation.
Right then, India batted for 9 balls after Lunch, added 12 runs and have set a target of 272 in 60 overs for England.

FOUR! Off the edge! Jimmy bowls it slightly short and around off, Shami goes back to punch but gets a healthy outside edge. It races past the flying first slip fielder for a boundary. INDIA HAVE DECLARED ON 298/8!
Shortish again, outside off, Shami hangs back to play through the line but misses.
Back of a length, on middle, Shami winds up for a big pull shot but it takes the higher part of his blade and goes tamely to mid on.

James Anderson to bowl from the other end. There is a slight halt in play. Mohammed Shami has some issue with his thigh pad and the umpires are waiting for someone from the Indian dressing room to come out. It's all taken care of now and play can resume.
What happened there?

Extra bounce and movement as it lands on a good length around middle, Jasprit Bumrah fails to defend and is hit near the box region. 8 from the over and India to continue with the bat. Are they aiming a lead of 300?
FOUR! Misfield. Fuller in length, around off, Bumrah throws all his power behind this shot and drills it down to mid on. Anderson fails to stop it with a dive and it speeds away to the fence.
This one again straightens from a good length around off, Bumrah is caught pushing and missing inside the line, again.

FOUR LEG BYES! Big movement on this delivery, probably landing on one of the cracks. A bouncer banged in around off, not getting up at all. It's sliding down, Bumrah tries to pull but it goes under his bat, clips his pads and races away to the fine leg fence.
Beaten again! On and around off, a length delivery, holding its line again, Bumrah tries to defend but misses.
Beats the bat! Back of a length, outside off and holding its line, Bumrah pushes inside the line and misses.
There is no news about India declaring. The English fielders are spreading. Mohammed Shami and Jasprit Bumrah to continue with their stand. Ollie Robinson to bowl...
... DAY 5, SECOND SESSION ...

Right then, the ball is now in India's court. They have a lead of 259 and have the option to declare now. Will Virat Kohli take that? Or will we see India continue with their batting? England won't mind now if things get delayed more as it will take crucial time out of this Test match. 64 overs left in the day's play so the required rate for England to win this Test match will be above 4. Let's see what is in store. Do join us at 12.40 pm GMT (1.40 pm local) for all the action after Lunch.

England lost the plot badly. Once Jasprit Bumrah arrived at the crease, their attempt was more about bouncing him out and probably giving him the taste of his own medicine. What happened with James Anderson on Day 3 may have clouded their minds as their lines and lengths went awry. Jasprit Bumrah and Mohammed Shami took a few blows but then gave it back as well. There were banters and sledging, and that only made these two batters mentally stronger. Shami and Bumrah have their best Test scores at the moment and their partnership has hurt England's chances massively. Bumrah did offer England one chance but Root dropped the catch and the pair has added close to 30 runs after that.

A session well and truly belonging to two individuals, Mohammed Shami and Jasprit Bumrah. Nopes, they are not bowling yet, they have done the miracle with the bat. An unbeaten stand worth 77 runs has taken the wind out of the English sails. The build-up before Day 5 was around Rishabh Pant but he didn't do much with the blade. England managed to strike early to remove both the overnight batsmen but they would not have imagined in their wildest dreams that India's number 9 and number 10 would put up a fight like this. It's been a sensational batting show by this pair. They started in a typical tail-ender fashion but slowly grew in confidence to play some proper cricketing shots. The lead is stretched to 259 runs after India scored runs at a rate above four in the morning session.
Tossed up, full and on off. Shami blocks it with authority. That's it for the first session and it's time for Lunch on Day 5.
Flatter delivery, on the stumps. Shami blocks it off the back foot.
Fuller and quicker, outside off. Bumrah looks to block but the ball goes off the outside edge towards backward point for one.
An action replay of the previous delivery as Jasprit Bumrah defends this one with ease as well.
Flighted delivery, outside off. Bumrah strides forward and defends it on the full.
Loopy ball, outside off. Bumrah strides forward to defend and does so well.
Length ball, around off and Shami defends it off the front foot.
A touch fuller this time, trying to swing it in from outside off. Shami gets behind the line of the ball to block it.
Length ball, on off. Shami stays solid in defense.
Length again, outside off. Bumrah eases it through point and collects a run.
Length ball, coming in on middle and leg. Shami tucks it with ease towards deep square leg for a single.
Good length delivery, outside off. Shami looks to push but gets beaten.
Flighted again, around off and Shami looks to go big again. He does not get any timing as the ball lands around mid on. The fielder from long on collects it. The batsmen get a single.
Tossed up and Shami defends this one.
Fuller delivery, on off, turning in and holding up a bit too. Shami pushes it back to the bowler. A bit uppish but doesn't carry to Moeen.

SIX! BANG! FIFTY for Mohammed Shami! Flighted delivery and Shami has decided that he will deposit this one back into the stands and does just that. Shami smokes it way over the mid-wicket fence for a huge hit. What a half-century this has been, off only 57 balls! Sensational. He raises his bat and the Indian spectators are loving it. The lead has also crossed the 250-run mark.
Once again there were some words exchanged in between the overs.
FOUR! A touch short on off stump. Shami hangs back and hits it with the spin and into the vacant wide long on region for a boundary.
Tossed up, around off. Bumrah slogs it in front of square leg for a run.
Short again, this time swinging down leg. Shami looks to pull but misses.
Short in length, around middle and leg. Bumrah pulls but the ball goes off the gloves towards fine leg and they get a run.
Shorter delivery, with some away movement, well wide of the off stump. Bumrah looks to pull but decides against it.
Length again, outside off. Bumrah taps it towards cover-point.
Length ball, nipping in from around off. Bumrah stays solid in defense.
On a good length, around off. Bumrah drives it to mid off.
Loopy delivery, on middle. Bumrah gets down on his knees and sweeps it to deep square leg for a single.
Fuller and quicker, just outside off. Bumrah plays it late and the ball goes off the outside edge, well wide of first slip and towards third man. The batsmen get a couple.
Flighted delivery, outside off. Bumrah puts out a stride and defends it well.
Quicker one, short and around off. Shami cuts it off the back foot to deep cover for one. He's eyeing a personal fifty now.

FOUR! SMACKED! Tossed up, very full. Shami takes full advantage and swings it over the bowler's head and into the fence at long on. That one bounced just in front of the rope as James Anderson ran back. Root is not liking this a single bit.
Flatter one, on off. Shami nudges it towards point.
Back of a length, jags back in from off. Bumrah watchfully keeps it out on the on side.
Length ball, on off. Bumrah pats it back to the bowler.
The Indian physio runs out. Jasprit Bumrah to go through the mandatory concussion check. He is looking fine and has a big smile on his face.
TWO LEG BYES! Short ball, on middle. Bumrah swings again and the ball goes off the helmet towards the third man region. The batsmen get a couple of leg byes.
Quick bumper this time, outside off. Bumrah swings and misses.
Fullish delivery, on off. Bumrah drives it towards mid off.
Pitched up, around off and nipping back in. Shami works it through mid-wicket for a run.
Tossed up again and kept out again by Bumrah.
Flighted delivery and Bumrah drives it to the cover region.
Tossed up delivery, on off. Blocked out by Bumrah.

A touch shorter and Shami rocks back to work it towards deep square leg for one. 50 partnership up between these two. The Indian fans are loving what they are seeing. Virat Kohli as always is pumped up.

DROPPED! Genuine chance and the skipper, Joe Root has fumbled the catch at first slip. Flighted delivery, around off and Bumrah looks to block but instead, he gets the outside edge and the ball goes through Root's hands towards third man for a run.
Tossed up, on middle. Bumrah blocks it out.
Moeen Ali is back on.
Length ball, on off. Shami stays solid in defense.

Again it goes past the fielder, this time over Jonny Bairstow at mid-wicket. Full, swinging delivery, on middle and Shami flicks it over mid-wicket for a couple. Probably, Jonny got some fingertips on the ball.
Length ball, on the stumps. Shami blocks it off the back foot.

FOUR! Full and straight. Shami leans into the shot and hits it over the fielder at short mid-wicket and into the fence. Cracking shot. Jonny Bairstow was the fielder attempting to catch but it's up and over him.
Beaten this time. Length ball, in that channel outside off. Shami looks to block but gets beaten.
Fullish delivery, on off and swinging in. The ball gets the inside edge onto the pads and pops up to the vacant short leg region and lands safe. They get one.
James Anderson is back into the attack.
James Anderson is brought back into the attack. Jimmy vs Bumrah, this would be spicy. Bumrah bowled quite a few bouncers on Anderson's body. Will James Anderson take revenge?
Gets behind the line of the delivery and blocks it towards mid on.
Lands it on a length and outside off, Bumrah offers a textbook forward defense shot. The ball rolls to point. Bumrah is admiring his shot and Shami calls him through for a run. 250 up for India.
Fuller in length and outside off, Bumrah drives but finds the mid off fielder.
Mark Wood is off the field and is applying an ice bag on his shoulders. Must be sore.
Good length ball on middle, Shami closes the face and works it behind square leg for a single.
Angling in and moving away, outside off, Shami pushes at it and misses.
Angles in a length ball on off, Shami defends it watchfully.
Too full and on off, Bumrah safely jams it out to complete the over.
Slower through the air, full and on off, Bumrah leans forward and defends.
Flatter one, short and on middle, Shami goes back and hits it through mid-wicket for a single.

FOUR! Smashed away! Moeen bowls it fuller and outside off, Shami crunches his drive through covers for a boundary. That's the reward for waiting for a delivery that's pitched up to you. The lead is now 220.
Slightly quicker and fuller outside off, Shami tries to defend but it beats the outside edge.
Loopy and full on off, Shami defends it near his front pad.
Good length ball on middle, straightening a touch, Bumrah is firmly behind the line with a straight bat and defends it back.
Presses forward to a full ball outside off and drives it superbly through the line. Finds the cover fielder.
Curran goes fuller and serves it on middle, Shami eases it off his pads behind square leg for a single.
Slips a length ball down the leg side, Shami tries flicking but misses.
Full in length and on middle, Bumrah clips it towards square leg for a run. This stand is now 33.

EDGY FOUR! Back of a length, around off and angling in with some extra bounce, Bumrah tries to defend but it takes the outside edge and flies down to third man for a boundary. It is all going India's way.
Tossed up ball on off, Shami presses forward in defense.
Spinning in from around off, full in length, Shami gets forward to defend and it runs down the slope at third man after taking the outer half. A couple of runs more.
Leans forward this time, to a fuller length delivery outside off and defends.
Flatter and outside off, Shami is on the back foot in defense.
Moeen drags his length short and bowls it around off, Shami punches it to deep cover for a couple.
Beaten! Floated off spinner, landing full outside off, Shami gets forward to defend but it doesn't sin in much and beats the outside edge.
Moeen Ali is into the attack now.
Curran switches to 'round the wicket and bowls a harmless length ball outside off, Bumrah allows it through.
Shami is getting confident. Curran lands it full and outside off, Shami leans into the drive and crunches it to the left of mid off. Another run, easy-going for the Indian tail.
Fuller in length and on middle, Shami tickles it fine down to fine leg and takes a couple of runs.
Around off, on a length and angling away, Shami pushes it with an angled bat to covers. This stand is now worth 21 runs and will be annoying England.
Too full in length and around off, Shami drives it to covers. Finds the fielder who fumbles slightly and Shami looks for a run. He is sent back.
Angling away from the batsman, outside off, Bumrah puts his bat at it and gets it away off the outer edge. The ball runs wide of gully and they take a single.
Sam Curran has been brought into the attack for the first time today.

Hits the stumps at the other end, AGAIN! Fullish and on off, Bumrah drives it through the line, drills it straight back and it collides with the stumps. The ball deflects to the right of mid on and they take a single.
Good length ball, outside off and angling in, Bumrah defends it back.
Make it 201. Wood bangs in a short ball on off, jumping onto the batsman, Shami leans back and keeps it out through point for another run.
Short in length, around middle, Bumrah turns and pulls it down to fine leg for a run. LEAD IS NOW 200! The Indian spectators in the crowd applaud and Virat Kohli is also clapping.
Pitches it up and around off, a spicy delivery, Jasprit Bumrah clears his front leg and pushes it down to mid on.
Back of a length, around off, Shami goes back and pushes it through point for a single.
Short and wide outside off, Bumrah has a lazy poke at it and misses.
Easy single. Fullish and around off, Shami works it easily through square leg for a run. The lead moves to 198.
Too full in length and on middle, 81 mph, Bumrah forces it down to long on and takes a single.
Slower and fuller on off, Bumrah gets forward and defends.
Shortish and on off, Shami somehow pushes it in the gap at covers for a run.
Bangs in a short ball on middle, Bumrah pulls it down off the top edge to fine leg for a single.
Full toss on off, Shami knocks it down to mid on and looks for a run. He is sent back as the fielder misses his shy at the striker's end.
Fullish and on off, Bumrah goes hard at it and inside edges it towards fine leg for a run.

During the over break, Shami and Bumrah were seen involved in banter with Buttler. That was an animated banter with Bumrah pointing his fingers at Jos. The umpires intervened and calmed things down. The replays are shown and it seems Mark Wood initiated that banter. The umpires asked both the parties to seal their lips.

Mandatory concussion check. The physio is on the pitch to check on Jasprit Bumrah as he got hit on the helmet. We hope that he is fine and meanwhile, the players also take a Drinks break. It's been an exciting morning session thus far. There were no heroics from Rishabh Pant but the current pair is showing some fight in a typical tailender style. India lead by 193 runs now.
Bang on the helmet! A well-directed bouncer, Bumrah fails to pull and it goes off the back of his helmet to third man. Shami wants a run but he is sent back.
Digs in a short ball outside off, Bumrah allows it through.
Short in length and outside off, slower in pace, Bumrah tries to swing his bat again but misses.

FOUR! Pulled to deep point, yes, it has gone to the off side. Back of a length, around off, Bumrah shapes up for the pull shot but it takes a thick outside edge and runs away to the deep point fence. Virat Kohli is all fired up in the Indian balcony.
Slower length ball on off, Bumrah forces it down to long on for a single. 7 runs added by the current pair and India's leading is inching close to 200, only 11 short.
Hits straight to the stumps at the other end. Fuller in length and outside off, Bumrah drives it straight back but for no run as the ball deflects off the stumps to mid off.
Slower one, swinging in the air and landing outside off, Bumrah is very early with his attempted slog sweep and misses.
Short and wide outside off, slapped to deep cover-point for a single.
Good length ball on off, Shami defends it from the back foot and keeps it out off the outer edge.
Up in the air, safe again. Short in length and on off, Bumrah pulls it to deep square leg and the ball falls in no man's land. A single is taken.
Wood ends the over with a fiery ball, just outside off. Shami dangles his bat at it but the ball goes agonisingly past the outside edge.

Edged but safe! Slower one, full land outside off, Jasprit Bumrah winds up for a mighty heave but gets an outside edge. It falls in front of the diving Buttler.
Goes for a big slog across the line but only manages to drag it off the inner half to mid on.
Jasprit Bumrah is the new man in.
Slower one again, full and around off, Bumrah gets his bat down on it somehow and hit it aerially. It's wide of mid on for a couple.

OUT! Ishant is a sitting duck! A clever change in pace from Ollie Robinson. He lands it close to off on a length and gets it to move back into the batsman. Ishant is late in attempting to flick it away and is struck on the pads. The appeal is made and the umpire raises his finger. Ishant takes the DRS but it's of no use. Plumb. The lead for India is 182.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Ollie Robinson

On a length and around off, Sharma opens the face of the bat and pushes it through point for a single.
Around off, on a length, angling in, Shami whips it across the line but the mid on fielder makes a fine stop.

Wood has another fall, right on the injured shoulder. Angling in around off, slightly fuller, Shami drives it back and Wood takes a tumble in his followthrough to stop the ball. Sometimes when the adrenalin is rushing, you don't remember your injuries.
Short and on off, zipping off, Shami tries to play the upper cut but misses.

Huge appeal for a catch! Not given. Joe Root has a word with his fielders and bowler and decides not to review. Two gentle deliveries to warm up and a nasty short ball to follow. Well-directed, Shami takes his eyes off the ball as he tries to fend it away. The ball goes past his gloves, probably took his left shoulder and ballons to gully. Rory Burns catches it, they appeal but nothing from the umpire. The replays confirm that it was off the shoulder.
Wood spears in a very full ball on middle and leg, angling down, Shami again fails to flick and it goes behind off his pads. A good stop by Buttler.
Starts with a full length ball down the leg side, Shami tries to flick but misses.
Bowling change. Mark Wood is on the field and he's ready to bowl.
Angling in, on a length around off, Shami plays it with soft hands and works it through square leg for one. The lead is now 180.
Too full in length and just outside off, Ishant brings down an angled bat and places it wide of gully to third man. A single.
Play and a miss! Fullish and outside off, Ishant aims for a big heave but fails to connect.
Back of a length, on middle and leg, Shami jumps and taps it down in front of square leg for one.
Short in length and outside off, Shami bends his knee and then tries to pull but misses.

FOUR! That's a good shot! He should take the lead as he is a better batter than Ishant. Full in length and outside off, Shami stands back and drives it on the up. It's aerial but in the gap at covers for a boundary.
Very full and around off, almost a yorker, Ishant walks across and flicks it through mid-wicket for two.
Anderson goes fuller and outside off, Ishant jumps down the track to drive it through the line but fails to connect.
Extra lift, from a shorter length outside off, Sharma fends at it but it flies over his gloves.
Walks across the stumps with another attempted flick but fails to connect.
Shortish and around leg, angling down, Ishant walks across the stumps, trying to glance but misses.
FOUR! All runs count from here. The Indian tail will go down swinging. Width outside off, Ishant throws his bat at it and the outside edge takes the ball flying over the slip cordon.
Angling down the leg side, Shami tries flicking but misses. Buttler makes a good stop as the ball was swinging a lot.
Extra bounce again, short and outside off, Shami goes on his toes and plays it down from the bottom half.
Back of a length, Shami pushes at it and misses.
Who will come in at number 9? Mohammed Shami has walked out to bat.

It's on a good length close to off and nipping away off the seam, Pant could have looked to play it a lot straight but his bat comes down at an angle as he pokes inside the line. The ball takes a healthy outside edge and Buttler makes no mistake to his left. India lead by 167 runs.
Commentary.Howout: c Jos Buttler b Ollie Robinson

Back of a length, on middle and off, Pant defends it from the back foot to the off side.

Fuller in length on middle, Pant closes the face of his bat and pushes it out safely to mid-wicket.
Anderson attempts for an inswinger but the line starts from middle and it takes the ball down the leg side. Pant fails to flick and it goes off his pads to backward square leg.

Back of a length, on middle and off, Pant taps it down towards mid-wicket and rotates the strike. One ball for Ishant to survive.
Beauty from Ollie! Lands it around middle and gets it to seam away, Pant tries to defend from the crease but is beaten on the outside edge.
No Mark Wood on the field.
Short and wide outside off, slapped to deep cover-point, no run taken.
Robinson gets close to the stumps and delivers it on a good length, Pant is forward in defense and it goes off the outer half through point. No run taken.
Starts with a length ball, angling away from the batsman outside off, Pant covers his stumps and shoulders arms.
Ollie Robinson is going to start from the other end.
Safely negotiated. Fuller and around off, jagging back in sharply, Ishant tries to defend but is hit on the pads. Probably outside the line and too high as well. Only a stifled appeal.
Good length delivery in the channel outside off, an outswinger, quite wide from the batsman and Ishant has an easy leave.
Anderson angles in a length ball on off, Pant walks forward and works it in the gap at mid-wicket for a run. Anderson has two balls to bowl at Ishant.
Beaten this time! Jimmy hurls across an outswinger, on a fuller length just outside off, Pant pushes at it tentatively and gets beaten.
Angling in, from a good length outside off, Pant stays back to defend it down.
Starts with a length ball around off, from 'round the wicket angle, Pant gets forward and defends it with gentle hands to cover-point. Seemed interested in a run but then returned.

Enough of build-up, let's get going with the action on the field. The English players are spreading around, Joe Root will have to find the right balance between attacking and defending. In walks Rishabh Pant, all the Indian hopes are pinned on him and along with him is Ishant Sharma, who has a decent defensive technique. Batting with the tail is an art, we have seen in the past how Steve Waugh, VVS Laxman and Michael Hussey used to smartly get runs by mixing aggression with defense. Can Pant do it? The second new ball is taken and it's James Anderson to speed in. Pant on strike, here we go...

It's an overcast morning and the English bowlers are warming up. We see Ollie Robinson, then Moeen Ali and then Mark Wood, yes, he is out there loosening up. That's a great sign if you are supporting England.

Pitch report - Michael Holding is near the surface. The West Indian says that the pitch is looking quite good, there are a few ball marks, a few indentations but nothing to suggest that the batsmen cannot score runs. But then, Holding talks about the variable bounce and cited the example of Cheteshwar Pujara's wicket who got a brute of a delivery with extra bounce. Reckons that Day 5 is going to be difficult for batting as on the other parts of the pitch, there is wear and tear, and some areas are worse than others. Mentions how Moeen Ali exploited the rough patches and then reminds that Ashwin is not there to utilize the rough against the right-handers.

Vikram Rathour, the batting coach of India, talked to the media after Day 4. He sounded happy with the performance of the Indian openers. Added that they always analyze when they get out and what was their thought process while playing the shot. Regarding Rohit's dismissal, Rathour replies that he will continue to play the pull shot as it has fetched him runs and the only thing is to be selective. On Virat Kohli, Vikram Rathour opines that there is no issue with Kohli and it was only a lapse of concentration.

How's Mark Wood? He injured his bowling hand last evening while preventing a boundary and was seen heavily strapped on the right shoulder. England would be sweating on his availability as his extra pace could be handy against the Indian tail. We will let you know about his fitness as soon as we get any updates. Nick Knight (on air) informed that they interviewed Wood a while back and he was not looking fully fit. The fast bowler will be going for some treatment and his availability is uncertain at the moment.

Ball Tampering, eh? One tweet from Virender Sehwag, another from Aakash Chopra and social media was flooded with ball-tampering posts. Once the whole footage was found out, it appeared nothing more than an accident. So, the moral of the story is that in this world of fake news, never believe screenshots or video clips that tell you only half the story. The incident involved Mark Wood and Rory Burns and it happened in the 32nd over. A defensive shot was played back to the bowler by Ajinkya Rahane and Wood tried to stop it with his boot and if you know Wood's love for football, he tried to nutmeg Burns who was coming to collect the ball. But accidentally, Wood's attempt got stuck below Rory's boot. There was no malice. It wasn't deliberate. Later on, Vikram Rathour, the batting coach of India, also echoed the same thoughts in his interview. End of the story.

Numbers game! How many runs will make India feel safe? That's the question. Sunil Gavaskar is in the studio and he comes up with his brave prediction. The Little Master says that anything between 180-200 and India can defend it. He further goes deep with his prediction and tells that India will win by 19 runs with two overs to spare. Wow! If that happens, we will be in for a cracking finish.

Hello and welcome everyone for the final day of the Lord's Test. This match is on a double-edged sword and you could not have asked for a better finish. Both teams have fought with great intensity and now a final push is required to take victory home. You can say England have the upper hand at the moment but one hour of Rishabh Pant's madness with the bat and things can change very quickly. Having said that, the English bowlers had a good night's rest and would be raring to go with the second new ball which is due now. It's going to be a mouth-watering battle. Anderson vs Pant - you just can't afford to miss it.

England are on top! They are into the bowling all-rounders and the second new ball is available. One believes they won't be wasting time in taking the second new ball. The question is, can they make quick work of the Indian lower-order or will we see some more fight from the Indians? They too would love to take the lead upto 200 and then you never know, with the ball turning, they can surely fancy their chances to take all the 10 wickets. All three results are still possible on the last day. Do join us for all the action at 1100 local (1000 GMT). Till then, goodbye and take care!

What a finish we have in store then for the final day! When India lost Kohli, Rohit and Rahul in the first session, many of us felt, that the Indian innings would be wrapped up quickly. That was not the case though as Pujara and Rahane showed a lot of fight. The two batted for around 50 overs and added 100. Rahane scored a half ton and Pujara was on course for one. However, it was Wood again who got the breakthrough for England and that one wicket just opened the floodgate as Moeen then got rid of Rahane and Jadeja. Ishant and Pant though then fought it out before bad light stopped play.

Now then, the umpires have got together. They are now having a chat and have asked the players to walk off as the light is not good enough. Maybe the umpires were fine till the time England bowled with the spinners. However, just as they thought of taking the second new ball, they have gone off and that should probably be it. IN FACT, IT IS STUMPS!

An important third session awaits.

India are in big trouble! The batters they have been relying on in this series have been dismissed. The batters who are batting out there are yet to get some runs in this series, they need to find form somehow. It is time for them to step up and what better time than when your team needs it desperately. They not only have to bat time but have to try and score runs too. A lot will depend on the current pair, can the two deliver or will England continue to dominate after the break? We will find out.

25 overs, 56 runs and 3 wickets in this session! Those numbers just show how good England have been. Root could not have asked for anything better this morning. If there were three wickets the hosts would have wished for early on then it would be the wickets of Rohit, Rahul and Kohli and they have got those three. Not only that, their bowlers have been extremely disiplined and have not let India score freely too. Also, the changes from Root have been outstanding. OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! Sam Curran brings out the Imran Tahir celebration as he runs around in joy! Why not? He has had a poor time so far in this Test, no wickets in the first innings, a duck that too a first ball duck with the bat but he has got the big fish, the Indian skipper who was looking solid, Virat Kohli. India are effectively 28 for 3. Once again Kohli did not need to play at that one. For the second time in this series he has fallen to a delivery which he could have easily left. It is on a length, it lands just outside off and angles away further. Maybe Kohli was worried about the ball coming back in or maybe he was just done in by the angle as Curran was constantly changing sides. Kohli has probably been sucked into the trap. He pushes at it, the ball goes off the outside edge and the keeper takes it. Kohli walks back shaking his head, he knows he has made a mistake. Still some time for Lunch, England would love another one. Also, this dismissal reminded me of how Sachin was dismissed 19 years ago to Pedro Collins. That same angle, the tall left-arm pacer, landed it around off and angled it away. Sachin poked at it, it found the edge and Jacobs did the rest. It was the third Test in 2002 between India and Windies in Bridgetown. India went onto lose that game by 10 wickets. They are in deep trouble here too.
